{"attack":true,"case":"The target's net-benefit formula is dimensionally inconsistent and its central mechanism claim is self-contradicting, violating std-crit-design clause (1). The mechanism states: 'The net benefit is recall_wrong × P(fragile-correct) − falseflag_rate_correct × P(fragile-correct),' which simplifies to (recall_wrong − falseflag_rate_correct) × P(fragile-correct). This expression is strictly positive whenever recall_wrong > falseflag_rate_correct, REGARDLESS of critic precision. Yet the claim and scope simultaneously require precision_wrong > 0.5 as a co-necessary condition for the strict-benefit zone. If precision is irrelevant to the net-benefit formula, the >0.5 threshold is theoretically unmotivated; if precision IS necessary (because removing wrong candidates only helps if the critic actually flags wrong candidates, not correct ones), the formula is missing a precision-dependent term and is dimensionally wrong — it conflates recall (the rate of flagging among wrong candidates) with the actual probability of removing a wrong candidate from the pool. The formula as written cannot distinguish a critic with recall=0.6, precision=0.51 from one with recall=0.6, precision=0.99, yet the mechanism claims only the former is in the benefit zone. This internal contradiction means the proposed experiment cannot cleanly test the stated mechanism: any result can be attributed to the unmodeled precision term, making the forbidden cases unfalsifiable against the actual (contradictory) theory.","counterexample":null}